04594nam a22008055i 9783110584776DE-B159720181207094303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||181207s2018    gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105847767 a10.1515/97831105847762doi  a(DE-B1597)490560  a(OCoLC)1078917373  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0041902bisacsh1 aBassino, Paola, eauthor.15aThe ›Certamen Homeri et Hesiodi‹ :bA Commentary /cPaola Bassino. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (242 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTexte und Kommentare ;v5900tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tTable of Contents -- tAbbreviations of editions and works of reference -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1: The tradition of the contest between Homer and Hesiod -- tPart 2: Textual tradition -- tPart 3: Text and translation -- tPart 4: Commentary -- tFigures -- tBibliography -- tGeneral index -- tIndex of Greek words -- tIndex of passages  aThis book provides a comprehensive study of the Certamen Homeri et Hesiodi, an influential ancient Greek text that narrates the lives of Homer and Hesiod and their legendary poetic contest. It offers new perspectives on the nature, uses, and legacy of the text and its tale of literary competition. Located within a recent trend in scholarship that treats ancient biographies as modes of literary reception, the first chapter discusses how, for authors throughout antiquity and beyond, staging an imaginary competition between Homer and Hesiod was an adaptable and flexible way to convey a diverse range of speculations on epic poetry. The study of the manuscript tradition reassesses the relationships between the text of the Certamen preserved in its entirety in one single manuscript, and a small number of fragmentary witnesses on papyrus. It also presents new textual evidence demonstrating the success and circulation of the text in the Renaissance, and a new critical edition with translation. The commentary focuses on how the text characterises the two poets and encourages reflection on their respective wisdom, aesthetic and ethical values, divine inspiration, and Panhellenic appeal. It also addresses the role of Alcidamas as a source for the Certamen and identifies other sophistic influences.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Dez 2018) 4aCertamen Homeri et Hesiodi. 4aTextual criticism. 4aarchaic Greek epic. 4aclassical reception.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE  DG 2019 Englishz978311061685908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2018 Englishz978311060400908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2018z9783110603095oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97831105834890 cprintz978311058284040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110584776423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110584776.jpg  a978-3-11-060400-9  EBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-061685-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE  DG 2019 English  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aZDB-23-DGDb2018  aZDB-23-DGGb2017